timeline_data.body:
The failing test dynamically generates a new `java.lang.Object` class with injected fields. It then runs `javap` with the `-bootclasspath` option, providing the newly generated `java.lang.Object`, and checks whether the injected fields appear in the output.

I tried running the test with the RI, and it appears that `-bootclasspath` is ignored in both OpenJ9 and the RI, likely for security reasons.

@pshipton @tajila Is this a planned change for JDK24?

> In this case, the -bootclasspath specific test case should be disabled from JDK11+.

Since it's working in jdk 11 - 21 we should only disable for jdk24, if necessary.

I tried a simple test of `java -bootclasspath` on jdk24 and it does seem to be working.
```
jdk/bin/javap -bootclasspath /home/peter Test
Compiled from "Test.java"
public class Test extends java.lang.Thread {
  public Test();
  public static void main(java.lang.String[]);
  public void run();
}
```

Another test to read a different version of Object.class
```
jdk/bin/javap  -bootclasspath /home/peter Object
Compiled from "Object.java"
public class Object {
  public Object();
  public static void main(java.lang.String[]);
}
```

